<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,758,951,977]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,560,951,977]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diphascon (Diphascon) recamieri</emphasis>
(Richters 
<number box="[691,749,951,977]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1911.0">1911</number>
)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,951,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
The three specimens found had smooth cuticles. The drop is present between the buccal and pharyngeal tubes, which are narrow. Two rod-shaped macroplacoids and a microplacoid are within the pharyngeal bulb. Cuticle bars (as in other 
<taxonomicName box="[435,562,1072,1097]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Diphascon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[435,562,1072,1097]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diphascon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, and no thin cuticular swelling as in 
<bibRefCitation author="Dastych" box="[1081,1272,1072,1098]" pageId="17" pageNumber="28" refString="Dastych, H. (1985). West Spitsbergen Tardigrada. Acta Zoologica Cracov, 28 (3), 169 - 214." type="journal article" year="1985">
Dastych (
<number box="[1193,1253,1072,1098]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1985.0">1985</number>
))
</bibRefCitation>
are present in the inner side of the double-claws on the first three pairs of legs, although it has not been reported in other studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Dastych" box="[247,414,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="28" refString="Dastych, H. (1985). West Spitsbergen Tardigrada. Acta Zoologica Cracov, 28 (3), 169 - 214." type="journal article" year="1985">
Dastych 
<number box="[353,414,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1985.1988">1985</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dastych" box="[427,490,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="28" refString="Dastych, H. (1988). The Tardigrada in Poland. Monografie Fauny Polski, 16, 1 - 255." type="journal article" year="1988">1988</bibRefCitation>
). Body size ranged from 
<number box="[787,912,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="506.0" valueMax="572.0" valueMin="440.0">440 to 572</number>
μm, mean 
<number box="[1045,1089,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="502.0">502</number>
μm (SD 
<number box="[1197,1230,1152,1178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="66.0">66</number>
). The species has been cited for Europe, Asia, 
<collectingCountry box="[491,592,1192,1218]" name="United States of America" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">America</collectingCountry>
and the Arctic. In the Iberian Peninsula, it has been recorded for 
<collectingCountry box="[1369,1436,1192,1218]" name="Spain" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mihelcic" box="[159,335,1231,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="29" refString="Mihelcic, F. (1954) Contribution al conocimiento de los tardigrados en Espana. Estudio sistematico-ecologico. Anales de Edafologia y Fisiologia Vegetal, 13, 103 - 109." type="journal article" year="1954">
Mihelčič 
<number box="[272,335,1232,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1954.0">1954</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[355,602,1232,1257]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Diphascon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="recamieri">
<emphasis box="[355,602,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diphascon recamieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only appeared at three sampling points (Table 
<number box="[1151,1167,1232,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
), only in LF samples.
</paragraph>
